## Automorphisms.
An isomorphism from a group formula_1 to itself is called an automorphism of this group. Thus it is a bijection formula_109 such that
formula_110
An automorphism always maps the identity to itself. The image under an automorphism of a conjugacy class is always a conjugacy class (the same or another). The image of an element has the same order as that element.
The composition of two automorphisms is again an automorphism, and with this operation the set of all automorphisms of a group formula_28 denoted by formula_112 forms itself a group, the of formula_84
For all abelian groups there is at least the automorphism that replaces the group elements by their inverses. However, in groups where all elements are equal to their inverse this is the trivial automorphism, e.g. in the Klein four-group. For that group all permutations of the three non-identity elements are automorphisms, so the automorphism group is isomorphic to formula_114 and formula_115
In formula_116 for a prime number formula_117 one non-identity element can be replaced by any other, with corresponding changes in the other elements. The automorphism group is isomorphic to formula_118 For example, for formula_119 multiplying all elements of formula_120 by 3, modulo 7, is an automorphism of order 6 in the automorphism group, because formula_121 while lower powers do not give 1. Thus this automorphism generates formula_122 There is one more automorphism with this property: multiplying all elements of formula_120 by 5, modulo 7. Therefore, these two correspond to the elements 1 and 5 of formula_124 in that order or conversely.
The automorphism group of formula_125 is isomorphic to formula_126 because only each of the two elements 1 and 5 generate formula_124 so apart from the identity we can only interchange these.
The automorphism group of formula_128 has order 168, as can be found as follows. All 7 non-identity elements play the same role, so we can choose which plays the role of formula_129 Any of the remaining 6 can be chosen to play the role of (0,1,0). This determines which corresponds to formula_130 For formula_131 we can choose from 4, which determines the rest. Thus we have formula_132 automorphisms. They correspond to those of the Fano plane, of which the 7 points correspond to the 7 non-identity elements. The lines connecting three points correspond to the group operation: formula_133 on one line means formula_134 formula_135 and formula_136 See also general linear group over finite fields.
For abelian groups all automorphisms except the trivial one are called outer automorphisms.
Non-abelian groups have a non-trivial inner automorphism group, and possibly also outer automorphisms.

